org.sbrubbles.javadoc.taglets

Class IncludeFileTaglet

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.sbrubbles.javadoc.taglets.IncludeFileTaglet
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    com.sun.tools.doclets.Taglet

    public class IncludeFileTaglet
extends Object
implements com.sun.tools.doclets.Taglet
    Inserts the content of a text file in the documentation, inline and verbatim.

    Usage example

    /**
 * Something like this: {@include.file #cs:utf-8 resources/usage.txt}
 *
 * As seen below, HTML is escaped:
 * <script>alert("STOP! Hammer time!");</script>
 */

    Syntax

    This tag takes one or more arguments, separated by spaces: a path and optionally one of more flags, which must come before the path. The syntax for the arguments is as follows: 
     arguments ::= flag* path
 path ::= <a filesystem path>
 flag ::= '#' STRING ':' STRING

    Paths may be absolute or relative, with relative paths resolved at the root of the Javadoc directory. Flags are distinguished from the path by a leading # and trailing whitespace. Therefore, all tokens, starting from the first one lacking a leading #, are concatenated and parsed as a single path. For example, {@include.file resources/Mussum Ipsum.txt} reads the path as resources/Mussum Ipsum.txt.

    Author:
    Humberto Anjos
    See Also:
    toString(Tag), Java 7: Taglet Overview, Java 7: com.sun.tools.doclets.Taglet documentation, OWASP XSS Rule #1

      • toString

        public String toString(Tag tag)
        Returns the content of the file given in tag, HTML-escaped as in OWASP XSS Rule #1.

        The currently accepted flags are:

        • cs: the charset of the given file. Accepts anything Charset.forName(String) does, defaulting to UTF-8.

        Using an unrecognized flag is an error. Errors are handled by printing them in System.err and returning the empty string.

        Specified by:
        toString in interface com.sun.tools.doclets.Taglet
        Parameters:
        tag - the Tag representation of this tag.
        Returns:
        the text given in tag, or an empty string if there was any error.
        See Also:
        OWASP XSS Rule #1
